AddressCommonName.CommonPlaceName: FOUND KEYS TURNED INTO BARRACK "C" CUMBERLAND

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
Detailed Crash Investigation Supplement
(For review by the MSP Crash Team)




Section I. - Narrative
On March 16, 2023, Cpl. D. Ritchie of the Berkeley County West Virginia Sheriff's Office requested assistance with the imaging of an airbag control module (ACM) of a 2013 Subaru Impreza bearing West Virginia registration 02P176.  He advised the Subaru was involved in a fatal crash on March 4, 2023, at 1808 hours (case number 230304-054) in the 13200 Block of Apple Harvest Drive in Berkeley County, WV.  The Subaru was driven by Hunter Lloyd who died as a result of the crash.  Two other occupants of the vehicle were injured; Kaitlyn Brining and Taylor Riggleman.  The Subaru was traveling east on Apple Harvest Drive allegedly racing with another vehicle, when the second vehicle came to a stop in a curve in the roadway.  Lloyd allegedly swerved to avoid that vehicle causing the Subaru to travel across the westbound lane and leave the roadway.  The left side of the Subaru struck a utility pole, rotated around the pole and rolled onto its roof.  Cpl. Ritchie obtained a search warrant for the ACM of the Subaru.

On March 30, 2023, I responded to the Berkeley County Emergency Services with Cpl. Ritchie to assist in the execution of the search warrant.  The tires mounted on the wheels of the vehicle were the size recommended by Subaru.  Digital photographs were taken of the vehicle and the ACM was located under the instrument panel.  The factory installed cable was removed from the ACM and installed Bosch Crash Data Retrieval (CDR) cable number F00K108614.  The cable was connected to the Bosch CDR 900 tool which was connected to a laptop equipped with Bosch CDR software version 23.0.2.  The ACM was imaged and copies of the data were saved.

Two events were recovered from the ACM; a Frontal/Rear Crash (Record 1) and a Side Crash (Record 2).  A review of the data limitations did not show anything that would invalidate the data.  The ignition cycle at the time the ACM was imaged was 16,163.  The ignition cycle for the Frontal Rear Crash was 16,162, linking the data to this crash.  Both front seat belts were buckled.  The below chart shows five seconds of pre-crash data.  The data shows the Subaru indicated vehicle speed increased from 73.9 mph at -5 seconds up to 77.1 mph at -3.5 seconds.  The Subaru's indicated vehicle speed dropped 10.5 mph from -2 to -1.5.  From -1.5 to -1 the indicated speed dropped another 13.1 mph.  At -1.5 seconds the brakes were applied along with the Anti-lock braking system until the end of the recording.  The stability control was engaged for the last 1.5 seconds.  The steering input shows a left-hand steer for the first 1.5 seconds and then a right-hand steering input for the remainder of the recording, with the input increasing during the recording until the last half of a second.




The side crash was also recorded at 16,162 ignition cycles.  The pre-crash data for this record was the same as the front/rear crash.
 
Section II. - Attachments that were included in for this report:

The following items were attached to this report: 
CDR Report
37 Digital photographs uploaded to Veripic


 
Conclusion:
Based on the ACM data, on March 4, 2023, at 1808 hours, the Subaru was accelerating from 73.9 mph up to 77.1 mph with a left hand steering input, possibly to swerve around the other vehicle.  The steering input then changed to right hand, most likely initially due to driver input.  The right hand steering input increased over the end of the recording as the vehicle indicated speed decreased.  This would have been as the vehicle was rotating and sliding sideways prior to striking the utility pole.  No data was recorded on the ACM after the impact with the pole.

This case is closed for the Crash Team, a copy of this report will be provided to the Berkeley County Sheriff's Office for their investigation.
